The paper focuses on improving few-shot learning for object recognition in complex scenes by incorporating contextual cueing. This involves using scene context semantics to recognize new concepts more easily. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). Additionally, the paper proposes a Class-conditioned Context Attention Module (CCAM) and a flexible gating mechanism, which are both related to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also conducts extensive experiments on a dataset, which involves evaluating the performance of the proposed model (cs.LG). Furthermore, the paper involves natural language processing (NLP) techniques, such as contextual cueing, which falls under the sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper involves information retrieval (IR) techniques, such as recognizing objects in complex scenes, which falls under the sub-category of cs.IR.
